#sendology @european_vintage_cars Follow @sendology.101----------------------------------------1983 BMW M1 Le Mans car Team Warsteiner The BMW M1 was not only raced at the one-model Procar championship which supported the F1 races but also participated multiple years at the prestigious 24 hours of Le Mans endurance race.The BMW M1, Munichâ€™s only mid-engined production car, competed at Le Mans over seven years from 1979 - 1986. During this time a total of twenty-two M1s qualified for the 24h race, with seven finishes and two class wins. With these modest results, the M1 could not find success at Le Mans which was due to two major reasons: Strong competition and poor reliability. The car seen in the photos was a sole M1 that participated in the 1983 race, the #90 Warsteiner entry. It performed quite well by qualifying first in class against several Porsche 930 turbos and 928â€™s. On track to win its class, the M1 made steady progress towards the front, despite losing nearly two and a half hours to repair bodywork and replace gearbox bolts. But the Sunday morning ended after 7:00 am when the gearbox failed. The car had climbed to 19th position overall.Along with a lack of power and poor reliability many problem areas afflicted M1s at Le Mans. Engine failures were common, resulting in the biggest number of retirements. An Achilles heel of the M1 engine was the crankshaft harmonic damper. Failure of this component occurred quite often, and not only led to downtime in the pits to replace the damper but also led to engine failure if the problem was not noticed early. Gearbox failures were common and the pit crew had to rebuild them quite often during the races. 1983 BMW M1 Le Mans car Team Warsteiner The BMW M1 was not only raced at the one-model Procar championship which supported the F1 races but also participated multiple years at the prestigious 24 hours of Le Mans endurance race.The BMW M1, Munichâ€™s only mid-engined production car, competed at Le Mans over seven years from 1979 - 1986. During this time a total of twenty-two M1s qualified for the 24h race, with seven finishes and two class wins. With these modest results, the M1 could not find success at Le Mans which was due to two major reasons: Strong competition and poor reliability. The car seen in the photos was a sole M1 that participated in the 1983 race, the #90 Warsteiner entry. It performed quite well by qualifying first in class against several Porsche 930 turbos and 928â€™s. On track to win its class, the M1 made steady progress towards the front, despite losing nearly two and a half hours to repair bodywork and replace gearbox bolts. But the Sunday morning ended after 7:00 am when the gearbox failed. The car had climbed to 19th position overall.Along with a lack of power and poor reliability many problem areas afflicted M1s at Le Mans. Engine failures were common, resulting in the biggest number of retirements. An Achilles heel of the M1 engine was the crankshaft harmonic damper. Failure of this component occurred quite often, and not only led to downtime in the pits to replace the damper but also led to engine failure if the problem was not noticed early. Gearbox failures were common and the pit crew had to rebuild them quite often during the races.
